<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910301-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>910301-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Proposes New Agency   To Develop Natural Gas</HL><DATE>03/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The White House is proposing to replace theindependent Federal Energy Regulatory Commission with a newagency within the Energy Department.   Vice President Dan Quayle said that creation of the newagency, which would be called the Natural Gas and ElectricityAdministration, &quot;will make it easier to develop natural gasas an important alternative to imported oil.&quot; The new agencywould be headed by an administrator who could be fired by thepresident.</LP><TEXT>   It isn't at all clear that Congress will approve thereorganization, however. Chairman John Dingell (D., Mich.) ofthe House Energy and Commerce Committee, said recently, &quot;Iwasn't enthusiastic the last time they tried to move FERCaround. I don't see why my enthusiasm should increase.&quot;Chairman Bennett Johnston (D., La.) of the Senate Energy andNatural Resources Committee said that his &quot;enthusiasm for asingle administrator is not very high.&quot;   Lawmakers, producer groups and pipeline companies all havecriticized the five-member commission in recent years asbeing slow to approve new gas pipeline capacity, althoughsome industry officials contend the situation has begun toimprove.</TEXT></DOC>